Title: Marvel Studios' Ant-Man and the Wasp - Official Trailer #1
Comment:
I just watched Ant Man & The Wasp for the 1st time today (took me 2 Months to watch it), I thought that it had a lot of Action and a bunch of Hilarious bits in the Movie

Here are my thoughts and Opinions on the Movie: 1. So this is what Scott was up doing after Violating the Accords and when all the Avengers were either fighting up in Space or battling it out in Wakanda and explains why he wasn't there.
2. It should've had a follow up like with Peter with Spiderman Homecoming, with Clint & Wanda having Cameo Appearances recruiting Scott to come to Germany to fight alongside Cap and what happened after getting out of the Raft. also Hope & Hank watching it all on TV and then they react and have to pack everything up and go on the Run.
3. Seeing Bill Foster (aka Goliath) in this Movie, I was hoping that a Giant Fight between Scott & Bill was gonna Occur.
4. Its nice to see Paxton be all Buddy-Buddy with Scott instead of him being all Hostile towards him like in the 1st Movie.
5. It was nice to see Hope & Cassie to interact with each other at the end (not what I was expecting but its close enough). If a 3rd Ant Man happens in Phase 4, I hope they bond more like Hope takes Cassie under her Wing and trains her in Martial Arts.
6. It was Awesome to see Hope finally become a Superhero, she's got some Amazing Moves. If she was in Civil War, I would've loved to see her fight against Natasha, I mean Black Widow vs The Wasp. But in Avengers 4, I wonder if she'll team up with her, Wanda and Gamora. ?
7. It was sweet that Hank & Hope finally reunited with Janet after 30 Years, too bad it was short lived due to Thanos activating the Infinity Gauntlet. I wonder how this will tie in to Avengers 4 and I hope Hank & Janet aren't gone for Good.

Title: Marvel Studios' Ant-Man and the Wasp - Official Trailer #1
Comment:
I liked the trailer, but I can see a small issue many people might have with it, and it's Hank taking the "Suitcase-Building", don't get me wrong, I laughed when I saw it, but, just like Scott running on the security guards hand-gun in the first movie, the Pym-Particles only move atoms closer, Hank is still moving a suitcase the weight of a full size building.
Unless the building itself is made of a material so light anyone could move it (but not the wind?), and resistant enough to hold it up (considering there is no foundation), but it will be one that MARVEL can just make up and never use again.
Also the PEZ dispenser would just bounce off the biker, but since he doesn't know it's still the weight of a tiny plastic item, he would be terrified, so that moment works completely.
I don't mean to hate on the movie before it's even out, I will watch it, and if it's anything like the original, I will like it very much, I just want to point out a flaw that the writers/producers/director are/is overlooking just to get visually nice or funny scenes (which they are), it's jumps in logic and ignoring ideas and statements given by the plot that are contradicted later on for these purposes, it can really anger people who take these movies too seriously (which you shouldn't, A because it's Ant-Man, and B because it's a movie!).

If, however, there is a logical explanation that appears it the comics of that was maybe mention it Ant-Man (like Hank developing an even better particle) that I might of missed, please tell me.

Title: Marvel Studios' Ant-Man and the Wasp - Official Trailer #1
Comment: This looks perfect. Someone in the Marvel Studios really understands Ant-Man's perspective: a working-class hero who tries to live a grounded life, but his powers make him Avengers tier. He can't return to a life of luxury or secret societies after he takes off the mask, and he can't make the mask his life. I hope they focus on the consequences of the Sokovia Accords, to show how a political group controlling someone with superpowers for their own agendas is a Bad Idea, and heroes gotta be free to chase the justice that doesn't exist in a flawed system. It doesn't have to be which side of the Accords is the correct one, just that there can be good and bad on both sides. And Ant-Man can do that, because he's someone who has to face the consequences of his actions unlike Tony or Cap who have the means to make whatever choice they want and not be overly affected by the consequences. They don't see how the Accords affect the little guy. I hope this is the direction Marvel takes because if not they need to call me.

Title: Marvel Studios' Ant-Man and the Wasp - Official Trailer #1
Comment:
It's weird how inconsistent these movies are with their physics. So in the first movie, some things retain their strength and weight even after becoming small (like, for instance, Ant-Man himself, as he punches a hole through the floor the first time he becomes small -- this makes sense, as it's a lot of weight concentrated on a very tiny area)... but a real tank can be used as a keychain decorator because for some odd reason, it loses its weight as soon as it becomes small. Then again, we have the first movie's villain who also keeps their weight, but only in some cases. In others (like the fight on the model train), he does not.

So in this trailer, we have a minature skyscraper that can be moved by a human being. Where did the skyscraper's weight go? If some of it was lost in transition, that would mean it would collapse when it is large again, but at the bare minimum, it would be blown away by the wind.
And then we have the car chase where apparently the miniature car keeps its weight again.

Don't get me wrong, I understand that it's a Marvel movie and I would never want to take anything like this seriously -- but the creators really need to decide how this "miniaturization" works, because as it stands, it is pretty inconsistent even within the scope of a single movie (or in this case, a trailer).

Title: Marvel Studios' Ant-Man and the Wasp - Official Trailer #1
Comment:
I'm sure this movie is going to be good, but I don't think I entirely like this trailer. Besides them being on the run, we have no idea what the plot of the movie is going to be. Ghost shows up for half a second, we haven't seen anything from the Microverse or Janet, and a good third of the trailer is footage from Civil War.
I'll chalk this up to them not having the CGI for a lot of scenes done yet, but even so, I'm not the biggest fan of these obnoxious all-action all-high-energy trailers. Furthermore, the director said this was going to be a romance movie, and we see none of that. Nor do we see a ton of humor, which the first movie was all about.
I'm sure the second trailer will be more engaging for me, but I wouldn't be surprised if they released this trailer when they did so it could run alongside Black Panther.

Ingredients

For the filling

5oz golden¬†caster sugar, plus 1 tbsp for sprinkling1 tsp ground¬†cinnamon2 tbsp¬†cornflour600g/1lb 5oz Bramley cooking¬†apples, peeled, cored, sliced

For the pastry

400g/14oz¬†plain flour, plus extra rolling2 tbsp¬†caster sugar1¬†lemon, zest only250g/10oz cold¬†butter, cut into cubes1 free-range¬†egg, beaten with 2 tbsp cold water, plus 1 free-range¬†egg, beaten, to glaze

¬†

Method

For the pastry, place the flour, sugar and lemon zest into a bowl and rub in the butter until the mixture resembles breadcrumbs. Add the beaten egg and stir with a round-bladed knife until the mixture forms a dough.

Set aside one-third of the pastry for the lid.

Roll out the remaining pastry on a lightly floured surface until the thickness of a pound coin and 5-7cm/2-3in larger than the pie dish. Lift the pastry over the rolling pin and lower it gently into the pie dish.

Press the pastry firmly into the dish and up the sides, making sure there are no air bubbles. Chill the fridge for a few minutes.

Preheat the oven to 200C/180 (fan)/Gas 6. Place a baking tray into the oven to preheat.

For the filling, mix the sugar, cinnamon and cornflour in a large bowl. Stir in the apples.

Place the apple filling into the pie dish, making sure that it rises above the edge. Brush the rim of the dish with beaten egg.

Roll out the reserved ball of pastry. Cover the pie with the pastry and press the edges together firmly to seal. Using a sharp knife, trim off the excess pastry, then gently crimp all around the edge. Make a few small holes in the centre of the pie with the tip of a knife. Glaze the top with beaten egg.

Lightly knead the pastry trimmings and re-roll. Cut into leaf shapes place all around the edge of the pie, slightly overlapping each other, and glaze with more egg. Sprinkle the pie with sugar and bake in the centre of the oven for 45‚Äì55 minutes or golden-brown all over and the apples are tender.
